## 7. Impact of Globalization and Non-State Actors on Foreign Policy

### 7.1 Globalization's Influence

- Globalization has intensified cross-border interactions, making isolationism untenable.
- States are increasingly interdependent economically, politically, and socially.
- Traditional state-centric foreign policy is challenged by transnational issues like climate change, terrorism, and pandemics ([UKEssays, 2018](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/politics/impact-of-globalization-on-foreign-policy.php?vref=1)).

### 7.2 Rise of Non-State Actors

- Intergovernmental organizations (IGOs), non-governmental organizations (NGOs), multinational corporations, and other non-state actors play significant roles in shaping foreign policy.
- IGOs like the United Nations, World Bank, IMF, and WTO facilitate cooperation but require states to cede some sovereignty.
- NGOs influence human rights, environmental policies, and humanitarian aid but face challenges in accountability and influence.
- The private sector contributes to sustainable development and economic interdependence ([Stengel & Baumann, 2017](https://doi.org/10.1093/acrefore/9780190228637.013.456)).

### 7.3 Hybrid Governance and Policy Complexity

- Foreign policy is increasingly made within hybrid governance networks involving states and non-state actors.
- This complexity requires new analytical frameworks beyond traditional state-centric theories.
- Democratic legitimacy and transparency in foreign policymaking are ongoing concerns ([Stengel & Baumann, 2017](https://doi.org/10.1093/acrefore/9780190228637.013.456)).

