## 8. Summary Table: Key Phases of U.S. Foreign Policy Evolution

| Period                      | Dominant Policy Approach      | Key Characteristics                               | Notable Events/Policies                              |
|-----------------------------|-------------------------------|--------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| 18th - 19th Century          | Isolationism/Non-intervention | Avoidance of alliances, focus on commerce        | Washington's Farewell Address, Jefferson's policies |
| Late 19th Century            | Expansionism/Imperialism       | Overseas acquisitions, military demonstrations   | Spanish-American War, Great White Fleet             |
| Early 20th Century           | Isolationism to Intervention   | Neutrality Acts, League of Nations proposal      | WWI entry, rejection of League of Nations           |
| WWII and After               | Full Interventionism           | Military engagement, global leadership            | WWII, United Nations formation                       |
| Cold War                    | Containment/Interventionism    | Anti-communism, alliances (NATO), proxy wars     | Korean War, Vietnam War, Détente                     |
| Post-Cold War               | Unipolar Multilateralism       | Global leadership, coalition-building             | Gulf War, New World Order                            |
| 21st Century                | War on Terror/Domestic-first   | Counter-terrorism, unilateralism, skepticism     | 9/11 attacks, Iraq War, Afghanistan War             |
| Contemporary Era            | Complex Multilateralism        | Globalization, non-state actors, hybrid governance| Climate change, China policy, pandemic response     |

